[1] Trinidad
Date: Tue 26 Feb 2008
Source: Trinidad and Tobago's Newsday [edited]
<http://www.newsday.co.tt/news/0,73925.html>


Chief Medical Officer Dr Rohit Doon yesterday [25 Feb 2008] said
there have been 108 confirmed dengue cases reported for the 1st 7
weeks of this year [2008]. He said the cases were "generalised"
throughout the country, with poor hygiene contributing to the
transmission of the fever [virus]. Speaking to reporters following a
media briefing for the Health Ministry's 100-day plan update at
Crowne Plaza, Port-of-Spain, Doon said most clusters of dengue cases
occurred in places "where the hygiene is bad."

He said community hygiene and reduction of breeding places were key
to preventing dengue. Referring to the cases which occurred recently
at Freeman Road, St Augustine, Doon said this was an "unplanned
community where people stored water in barrels, and again the risk of
breeding was found in these containers filled with water." Doon said
hygiene in unplanned communities tends to be bad.

He said 4 confirmed dengue cases have been detected in Freeman Road.
He said the atypical dry season was also contributing to the breeding
of the _Aedes aegypti_ mosquito, which loves clear standing water.
"The transmission opportunities are much greater than they would be
in a typical dry season, and that's a real event for us to learn how
to cope with the real risk of transmission in this atypical dry season."

Doon said spraying for the infected _Aedes aegypti_ mosquito was
taking place in Cunupia and other areas with reported cases of dengue
fever. He said the aim was to break the cycle of transmission and
knock down the adult mosquitoes.

[Byline: Lara Pickford-Gordon]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail Rapporteur Brent Barrett

