[3] Brazil (Bahia)
Date: Sat 1 Mar 2008
Source: G1 [in Portuguese, trans. & summ. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://g1.globo.com/Noticias/Brasil/0,,MUL333580-5598,00-CASOS+DE+DENGUE+AUMENTAM+QUASE+NA+BAHIA.html>


Currently, there are 13 municipalities with outbreaks of the disease
in the state. Cases in the capital are under-reported, says the
Secretariat of Health of the State.

While in Brazil the number of dengue cases dropped 39.7 percent in
the 1st 2 months of this year [2008] in relation to the same period
of 2007, according to data from the Ministry of Health, Bahia
recorded an increase of nearly 110 percent in [numbers of] notified
[dengue cases].

According to the State Secretariat of Health (SESAB), from 1 Jan - 25
Feb 2008, there were 3263 [dengue case] notifications. In the same
period last year [2007], the number was 1563. In Salvador, the survey
done by the Municipal Health Secretariat (SMS) did not correspond to
the projection by the state and portrays a decline of nearly 60
percent. The data, however, are disputed by SESAB.

According to the SMS, in January this year [2008], there were only 70
[dengue case] notifications against 170 in the same period of 2007.
Up to 10 Feb 2008, there were recorded only 113 [dengue case] notifications.

However, the SESAB coordinator of vector transmissible diseases,
Jesuina Castro, has stated that there has been under-reporting in the
state Capital on account of constant strikes by community health
officials who are responsible for control of the disease. "These
numbers do not correspond to reality. We believe that these 70 cases
should be multiplied by 10," she asserted. She also mentioned that
the municipal health posts are not forwarding their data frequently.

According to SESAB, the situation in Bahia is worrying. Currently,
there are 13 municipalities with outbreaks of the disease.

Throughout state, there have been 12 suspected serious dengue cases,
with 5 confirmations. Of the others, 4 were discarded, and 3 are
under investigation by the Central Laboratory of the state. Two
suspected dengue deaths also are being investigated.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-PORT <promed@promedmail.org>

[Indeed, there is no need to comment; the facts are there; 2008
promises to be bad or worse than 2007. I hope I am wrong. - Mod.LJS]

[Untimely, inaccurate case reporting is not unusual during an
outbreak, where different levels of government services are involved.
One hopes that the 2 agencies cited above can develop a reporting
system that functions more smoothly to provide timely, reliable data
needed for adequate treatment and disease control. - Mod.TY]

