[4] Brazil (Ceara)
Date: Fri 29 Feb 2007
Source: Jornal O Povo [in Portuguese trans. & summ. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://www.opovo.com.br/opovo/fortaleza/769469.html>


In 2008, there is considerable chance of a DHF epidemic to occur.
"There is a great chance of that happening," says the coordinator of
Health Promotion and Protection of the state government Secretariat
of Health (SESA), Manoel Fonseca. The increasing proportion between
the 2 manifestations [classical dengue and DHF] is frightening. In
1999, for every case of DHF, there were 3252 cases of classical
dengue. In 2007, the relationship was one to 83. "With more people
sensitized now from having contracted the disease before, [we] could
more easily see serious forms of dengue," says medical expert Ivo
Castelo Branco. Over the past 7 years, the numbers of DHF cases
increased 7350 percent in the State.

"We have to learn to live with DHF. What we do not want is the number
of deaths increase," says Fonseca. Last year [2007], there were 126
more cases than in 2006, a total of 298 cases and 10 deaths. The case
fatality rate was 3.3 percent and was an improvement over 2006, when
8.7 percent of patients (15 individuals) with DHF died. But the
fatality rate may reach less than one percent with early diagnosis
and proper treatment.

A team of health officials have a list of 3000 buildings considered
strategic points in the control of _Aedes aegypti_ in Fortaleza.
Among them are vehicle tire places, deposits of construction
materials and scrap, to be visited 5 times a year.

In the Capital, 75 000 private homes are closed, which hinders the
access of the officials.

In Ceara, 72 percent of the municipalities have high risk of dengue;
21 percent are of medium risk; 6 percent are considered at low risk,
and 1.4 percent not at risk.

Usually, an epidemic occurs after the entry of a new dengue virus
serotype, as in 2003. The following year, the natural trend is that
the number of cases decreases as the population becomes immune. Many
people had the disease caused by [dengue] virus 2, for example. The
problem is that of the 4 types of dengue viruses, 3 are currently
circulating in Ceara. For 3 years, the state has had a high number of
cases, more than 20 000.

_Aedes aegypti_ is becoming resistant to insecticides; only 30
percent of the mosquitoes die [presumably after insecticide treatment
- Mod.TY].

The fatality rate from DHF in Brazil is the highest in Latin America,
at 10 percent. Worldwide, the fatality rate is 5 percent. Ceara
recorded a case fatality rate of 3.3 percent in 2007.

Some features of Ceara that hinder the fight against dengue include
the need to store water, including in the capital, and the use of
water coolers in many homes.

[Byline: Mariana Toniatti da Redacao]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-PORT <promed@promedmail.org>

[Unfortunately for this county, the day of serious dengue disease and
lethal outcomes has arrived. Everyone knew that the day would come,
but health authorities continue stating that dengue is being
controlled. It is not, and that is the truth. - Mod.LJS]

******
[5] Brazil (Rio de Janeiro)
Date: Tue 25 Feb 2008
Source: O Globo [in Portuguese, trans. & summ. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://oglobo.globo.com/rio/mat/2008/02/25/estado_do_rio_registra_8_mil_casos_de_dengue_14_mortes_por_causa_da_doenca_este_ano-425952037.asp>


The state of Rio de Janeiro has already registered 14 deaths from
dengue this year [2008]. Of these, 12 were reported in the capital;
one in Duque de Caxias, in the Baixada Fluminense; and the other in
Campos in the northern part of the state.

According to the Secretariat of Health, most deaths are children.
Just in the city of Rio de Janeiro, of 12 deaths, 9 were children.
According to the latest survey by the Secretariat of Health, the
disease has affected 8485 people in the state just in January 2008.
Last year [2007] during the same period, 3229 cases were recorded. In
the city in 2008, there have been 7202 confirmed dengue cases versus
2926 for the same period of 2007.

Those who have had dengue virus type 3, which has been the most
common virus since 2002, who then contract dengue virus 2 have a
greater chance of developing a severe form of the disease. Among
children who died of DHF this year [2008], 4 lived in neighborhoods
that have had an outbreak of disease, with an incidence of over 300
cases for every 100 000 inhabitants.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-PORT <promed@promedmail.org>

[ProMED-PORT posted a subsequent report that was published in the 3
Mar 2008 issue of Terra
<http://noticias.terra.com.br/ciencia/ultimas/0,,OI2642249-EI715,00>
that indicated that another child died from dengue, reinforcing the
fact that 30 percent of dengue cases are in children, according to
the Secretariat of Health of Rio. Of 6027 registered dengue cases,
1800 were in children under 15 years of age. Most victims are between
5 and 9 years. Of the total of 14 deaths in the municipality, 12 are
of children in this age range. - Mod.TY]

[ProMED-PORT Mod.LJS commented: "It is now known that dengue causes
more and more serious cases with each year that passes and becomes a
childhood disease. That is what has happened in Southeast Asia and is
easily explained by what is known of dengue epidemiology and pathogenesis.

Perhaps the millions of reals (Brazilian currency) that are applied
without results trying to control _Aedes aegypti_ should be applied,
at least in part, in improving assistance to patients with dengue.
Currently, having dengue is a problem, and dying of it is a disgrace.]

[Unfortunately, in the absence of effective dengue virus vaccines,
the only preventive measure available currently is mosquito vector
control. Because _Aedes aegypti_ is so widely spread within
communities at risk of dengue outbreaks, public involvement is
essential in eliminating water catchments in which this mosquito
breeds in and around houses and other buildings. This is a gargantuan
task for public health officials to accomplish alone. - Mod.TY]

******
[6] Brazil (national)
Date: Sat 1 Mar 2008
Source: O Estado de Sao Paulo [in Portuguese, trans. & summ. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://txt.estado.com.br/editorias/2008/03/01/ger-1.93.7.20080301.1.1.xml&Diario
do Nordeste>


The numbers of deaths from severe dengue disease given by the
Ministry of Health comes to 225, but there were 101 more deaths than
those registered by the Ministry.

Dengue in Brazil has killed more than shown in reports released by
the Ministry of Health and state and local governments. The real
number of deaths by disease in 2006 and 2007, 326, is 45 percent
higher than the total of 225 deaths reported in the latest 2 years in
[Ministry] bulletins on the epidemiological situation for dengue, as
shown by newly reported data.

The Ministry as well as state and municipal governments in reports
disseminated to the public included only deaths from DHF. These
reports did not provide information on deaths by other forms of the
disease, which also can kill: classical dengue and dengue with
complications; classifications which are defined by the World Health
Organization (WHO).

According to the publication, WHO works only with DHF in order to
facilitate comparison between countries. The addition of data on
deaths from other forms of the disease (which increases the numbers
of dengue cases significantly) for last year [2007] indicates that
epidemics were recorded in 5 states, with more than 500 000 suspected
dengue cases, which increases the number of deaths from DHF. The
Ministry of Health said that in 2008, there has been a decrease in
the incidence of the disease by 40 percent.

The latest bulletin from the Secretariat of Health of Sao Paulo,
which compiled data through January this year [2008], reported that
last year [2007], the country registered 158 dengue deaths but did
not include deaths from other forms of the disease. However,
according to the information obtained from the internal report by the
state, there was a total of 210 dengue deaths, 33 percent more, 14 of
them from classical dengue and 82 from dengue with complications.

[Byline: Fabiane Leite]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-PORT <promed@promedmail.org>

[This article illustrates the difficulty in implementing case
classification and uniform, timely reporting when hospitals have to
deal with a high load of dengue patients and deaths in an epidemic
situation. It is not surprising that DHF cases are more easily
identified and reported under epidemic conditions. - Mod.TY]

******
[7] Peru
Date: 10 Feb 2008
Source: Boletin Epidemiol (Lima) 17 (06), 2008 [in Spanish, trans. &
summ. Mod.TY, edited]


In epidemiological week 06 [week of 10 Feb 2008], there has been
notification of 1406 classical dengue cases, 59 percent from the
Loreto health district. To date, 16 health directorates have reported
locally acquired dengue cases.

The Lima health district has reported 23 [dengue] cases, of which 4
have been confirmed, but these have been imported from Loreto (3
cases) and Ucayali (one case), areas where there are outbreaks
currently. The remainder of these (Lima) cases are probable. Of
these, 12 are probable classical dengue cases, have not been outside
of Lima, and are currently under investigation.

An analysis of the dengue epidemiological situation countrywide
indicates that there are dengue epidemic alert situations in the
health directorates of Loreto, La Libertad and Ucayali. There also
has been a case of DHF in Loreto and in Ucayali. In the Loreto
district, there has been notification of 831 classical dengue cases
through epidemiological week 06.

Control of _Aedes aegypti_, the dengue virus vector, faces serious
limitations due to lack of area treatment [fumigation] equipment, and
there is a high transmission risk due to the vector being disbursed
in 30 zones into which the city of Iquitos is divided, with an
average _Aedes_ index of 10 percent [presumably a household
infestation rate - Mod.TY].

--
Communicated by:
Juan Carlos Celis Salinas
Infectious Disease Physician
Peruvian Research Group in Infectious and Tropical Diseases
