[8] New Caledonia
Date: Wed 5 Mar 2008
Source: Marianas Variety [edited]
<http://www.mvariety.com/?module=displaystory&story_id=7723&format=html>


The dengue fever epidemic which was declared last month [February
2008] in New Caledonia has now affected some 104 persons since the
beginning of this year [2008], according to latest counts at the weekend.

Most of the known cases are concentrated in the capital Noumea and
its greater area, as well as other reported hotbeds in the
northeastern island of Lifou, part of the Loyalty group, and on the
Isle of Pines, south of the capital Noumea.

Health authorities in New Caledonia have last week stepped up the
status of what was formerly a "pre-epidemic" situation to a fully
fledged "epidemic" with regards to dengue mosquito-borne hemorrhagic fever.

Last week, as the number of known cases was only 72, New Caledonia
health director Dr. Jean-Paul Grangeon was already considering the
situation "worrying," mainly because of the apparently exponentially
increasing rate of the numbers of new cases.

The alarm comes as New Caledonia and its greater region are facing
severe weather conditions characterized by high humidity and heavy
rains, which are triggering factors for mosquito-borne diseases such
as dengue fever and malaria. The humid weather conditions entail the
persistence of still water spots.

The New Caledonia Health and Prevention department has for the past
few weeks stepped up its prevention and awareness campaign against
the potentially deadly virus, mainly because of the heavy rains and
the hot and humid conditions currently affecting New Caledonia.

As part of the prevention campaign, Noumea's health and hygiene
services have also deployed, since the beginning of this month [March
2008], a team of a dozen officers whose main task is to visit house
and property owners and convince them to clean any potential mosquito
breeding sites, such as still water contained in old tires and plant
pots or any bushy area on their compound that could also become a
nest for mosquito larvae.

An earlier dengue fever epidemic in 2003 killed as many as 20 persons
in New Caledonia.

In French Polynesia, health authorities are also closely monitoring
development of the dengue front.

Since the beginning of the year [2008], more than a dozen persons
were also reported infected.

Efforts are also underway in Wallis and Futuna, the 3rd French
Pacific territory, to closely monitor movements of persons to and
from neighboring New Caledonia, where over 20 000 residents of Wallis
and Futuna origin are permanently established.

Locally, information awareness campaigns have also been stepped up.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>

